  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_3' aria-label=\" Devendra Kumar versus The State (NCT of Delhi) & Anr. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('3','2025','2025_8_1095_1136','2025INSC1009'); ><font size='4'> <strong>DEVENDRA KUMAR<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>THE STATE (NCT OF DELHI) & ANR. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 8 S.C.R. 1095</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 1009</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010006332025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration High Court affirmed the order passed by the CMM directing registration of the FIR against the petitioner for offences punishable u/ss.186 and 341, Penal Code, 1860. Whether the CMM erred in involving the police in a complaint lodged by a Civil Judge for u/ss.186 and 341 of the I.P.C; whether the CMM erred in asking the police to investigate the complaint u/s.156(3) of the Cr.P.C instead of taking cognizance upon the complaint and issuing process to the petitioner; scope of s.195, CrPC. Headnotes&dagger; Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 20-08-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> SPECIAL LEAVE PETITION (CRIMINAL) No. 12373/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Disposed off</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_8_1095_1136','2025INSC1009','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col